<item rdf:about="http://tripletalk.wordpress.com/2008/10/22/social-networks-and-the-semantic-web/">
  <title>Social Networks and the Semantic Web</title>
  <description>There seems to be again a growing interest in the topic of social networks and the Semantic Web. Besides some publications here and there, I have recently attended the highly motivating seminar on&amp;#160; Social Web Communities , a full week get-together of computer scientists with a social inclination, in the middle-of-nowhere conference paradise that is Dagstuhl . Most of the week was spent in small groups and in the group I joined we had some fun formalizing the notion of ’surprise’, i.e. an unexpected connection between two people (or things) in a network. Another interesting development is the plan hatched ...</description>
  <dc:creator>Peter Mika</dc:creator>

  <dc:date>2008-10-22T11:53:21Z</dc:date>
  <planet:content xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" rdf:parseType="Literal">
<div>
<div class='snap_preview'><br />
<p>There seems to be again a growing interest in the topic of
social networks and the Semantic Web.</p>
<p>Besides some publications here and there, I have recently
attended the highly motivating seminar on&#160; <a href=
"http://www.dagstuhl.de/en/program/calendar/semhp/?semnr=08391">Social
Web Communities</a>, a full week get-together of computer
scientists with a social inclination, in the middle-of-nowhere
conference paradise that is <a href=
"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dagstuhl">Dagstuhl</a>. Most of the
week was spent in small groups and in the group I joined we had
some fun formalizing the notion of ’surprise’, i.e. an unexpected
connection between two people (or things) in a network.</p>
<p>Another interesting development is the plan hatched by Dan
Brickley and Harry Halpin to launch a <a href=
"http://www.ibiblio.org/hhalpin/homepage/drafts/soccharter.html">Social
Web Incubator group</a> within the W3C.&#160; Hopefully this will
take on the issue of representation, since other initiatives with
social and open in their names tended to focus on APIs and the
technical interoperability of applications. To kickstart all this,
the W3C is organizing a <a href=
"http://www.w3.org/2008/09/msnws/cfp.html">Workshop on the Future
of Social Networkin</a><a href=
"http://www.w3.org/2008/09/msnws/cfp.html">g</a> in January, in my
(current) hometown of Barcelona!</p>

<p>Lastly, all of this reminded me that I haven’t yet blogged about
my book, <a href=
"http://www.amazon.com/Social-Networks-Semantic-Web-Beyond/dp/0387710000">
Social Networks and the</a><a href=
"http://www.amazon.com/Social-Networks-Semantic-Web-Beyond/dp/0387710000"><img class="alignright"
title="Social Networks and the Semantic Web" src=
"http://www.cs.vu.nl/~pmika/images/book-cover-small.jpg" alt=""
width="120" height="177" /></a> <a href=
"http://www.amazon.com/Social-Networks-Semantic-Web-Beyond/dp/0387710000">
Semantic Web</a>. The book - pictured here on the right-
unfortunately costs more than it really should due to the low
number of copies, but it is fair to say that is a good summary of
the technologies around which this field revolves, including social
network mining from the Web, social network representations using
semantic technologies, social network analysis and visualization,
and proving social theories using social network data. The book is
based on my PhD thesis, and although it has been out for a year, it
probably still makes an interesting read for anyone who wants to
learn about this field.</p>
